        <p data-uuid="c58c26a3d93541758957774a33405cd7">Between 1865 and 1890, the number of miles of railroad track increased nearly fivefold. Wherever railroads were built, new towns sprang up and existing towns grew into bigger cities. Cities where major rail lines
            crossed, such as Chicago, grew rapidly. Railroads also increased western growth
            by offering free tickets to settlers. And as rail travel and shipping
            increased, railroads and related industries began employing more people.&#160;</p>
